a love of reading and books.

00:13:55.480 --> 00:13:59.350
In my historical narrative, I
didn't take the conventional

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:01.850
user-in-the-life-of-a-library
approach.

00:14:01.850 --> 00:14:04.400
Rather, I took a
library-in-the-life-of-the-user

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:05.700
perspective.

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:08.710
Because I wanted to trace the
history of the public library not

00:14:08.710 --> 00:14:13.960
so much by analyzing the words
of its founders and managers,

00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:17.380
but mostly by listening to the
voices of people who used them

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:19.650
since the middle of
the 19th Century.

00:14:19.650 --> 00:14:22.120
Thus, instead of a top-down view,

00:14:22.120 --> 00:14:25.060
"Part of our Lives" adopts
a bottom-up perspective

00:14:25.060 --> 00:14:29.720 position:56%
that features the voices of
generations of public library users.

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:33.110
Largely because of recent
technologies, uncovering many

00:14:33.110 --> 00:14:35.420
of these voices was not difficult.

00:14:35.420 --> 00:14:37.030
Time consuming, yes.

00:14:37.030 --> 00:14:38.500
But not difficult.

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:41.230
