00:16:01.480 --> 00:16:05.750
While sitting at a Cincinnati
public library desk in 1867,

00:16:05.750 --> 00:16:09.420
Thomas Edison would get excused
from duty under the pretense

00:16:09.420 --> 00:16:11.240
of being too sick to work.

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:13.990
And invariably strike a
bee-line for the library,

00:16:13.990 --> 00:16:17.030
where he'd spend the entire day
and evening reading such works

00:16:17.030 --> 00:16:21.090
on electricity as were to
be had, a friend recalled.

00:16:21.090 --> 00:16:26.600
In 1899, Wilbur and Orville Wright
came upon an ornithology book

00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:29.730
in the Dayton Public Library
that rekindled their interest

00:16:29.730 --> 00:16:33.220
in human flight, one of
their biographers writes.

00:16:33.220 --> 00:16:37.410
"By the time I was 12 or
14," Harry Truman recalled,

00:16:37.410 --> 00:16:40.270
"I had read every book in the
Independence Public Library,

00:16:40.270 --> 00:16:42.740
including the encyclopedias.

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:46.280
These books had a great
influence on me."

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:49.710
In a Detroit public library
reading room in the 1950's,

00:16:49.710 --> 00:16:53.610
a teenaged female pored over
comedians' printed monologue.

00:16:53.610 --> 00:16:56.740
She appeared in short
monodramas written by herself

00:16:56.740 --> 00:16:59.520
without makeup, and
hardly any props.

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:01.870
Lily Tomlin's biographer
later noted,

00:17:01.870 --> 00:17:04.120
"conjuring up not only
the personality

00:17:04.120 --> 00:17:07.650
of the characters she portrayed,
but also that of unseen people

00:17:07.650 --> 00:17:10.090
with whom she was talking."

00:17:10.090 --> 00:17:12.830
About the same time in
Hot Springs, Arkansas,

00:17:12.830 --> 00:17:16.590
10-year-old William Jefferson
Clinton discovered the Garland

00:17:16.590 --> 00:17:18.010
County Public Library.

00:17:18.010 --> 00:17:21.240
"I'd go there for hours,
browsing among the books.

00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:23.930
Especially those on
Native Americans."

00:17:23.930 --> 00:17:30.340
In 1971, 10-year-old Barak Obama
returned to Honolulu from Jakarta.

00:17:30.340 --> 00:17:34.160
"First place I wanted to be was
a library," he later recalled.

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:36.910
Often he had a specific
information need.

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:40.490
"One Saturday with the help of
a raspy-voiced old librarian

00:17:40.490 --> 00:17:44.600
who appreciated my seriousness,
I found a book on East Africa."

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:47.730
Obama wanted information
about Kenya,

00:17:47.730 --> 00:17:51.180
birthplace of his father,
a Luo tribe member.

00:17:51.180 --> 00:17:55.380
The Luo raised cattle and lived in
mud huts and ate cornmeal and yams

00:17:55.380 --> 00:17:58.480
and something called
millet, the book said.

00:17:58.480 --> 00:18:03.020
Their traditional costume was a
leather thong across the crotch.

00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:07.250
Shocked by what he read, Obama
left the book open-faced on a table

00:18:07.250 --> 00:18:11.130
and walked out without
thanking the librarian.

00:18:11.130 --> 00:18:14.480
All these people had information
needs an American public

00:18:14.480 --> 00:18:15.780
library met.

00:18:15.780 --> 00:18:19.000
And the anecdotes I've read nicely
fit the traditional discourse

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:23.600
of librarianship that focuses
primarily on information.

00:18:23.600 --> 00:18:26.320
In many respects, the
professional discourse functions

00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:28.760
like a big intellectual sandbox.

00:18:28.760 --> 00:18:32.900
Plenty of room to play with ideas,
but one nonetheless with limits.

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:34.450
A social boundary, if you will,

00:18:34.450 --> 00:18:38.180
in which the profession's leaders
employ a formal way of thinking

00:18:38.180 --> 00:18:41.980
to educate and enlighten members
who then implement what they learn.

00:18:41.980 --> 00:18:45.550
To improve professional service
for the public's greater benefit.

00:18:45.550 --> 00:18:47.570
For librarians, that translates

00:18:47.570 --> 00:18:50.370
into services they
institute and maintain.

00:18:50.370 --> 00:18:54.290
And collections, spaces, and
resources they make accessible.

00:18:54.290 --> 00:18:55.960
For most of its history,

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:58.570
librarianship's discourse
has focused on what

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:01.930
in the 18th Century was
called useful knowledge.

00:19:01.930 --> 00:19:05.300
In the 19th and 20th Century
was called "best reading" --

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:06.600
that's a phrase that's still

00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:09.810
in the American Library
Association's official motto.

00:19:09.810 --> 00:19:13.940
And in the late 20th, has
morphed into information.

00:19:13.940 --> 00:19:17.970
This focused term gives
particular meaning to the phrase,

00:19:17.970 --> 00:19:23.060
"access to information" that to
this day dominates the profession's

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:25.620
thinking and automatically
imposes boundaries

00:19:25.620 --> 00:19:28.850
on its intellectual sandboxes.

00:19:28.850 --> 00:19:33.080
But the American public library
is a unique civic institution.

00:19:33.080 --> 00:19:36.870
Because unlike other civic
institutions like courts

00:19:36.870 --> 00:19:39.890
and schools, people
don't have to use it.

00:19:39.890 --> 00:19:44.560
As a result, over the generations
users have heavily influenced the

00:19:44.560 --> 00:19:48.160
process of shaping library
collections and services.

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:51.020
Librarianship's discourse,
however, does not address

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:54.160
in any direct way this
kind of bottom-up pressure.

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:56.200
And for me was not
comprehensive enough

00:19:56.200 --> 00:20:00.200
to explain what I was discovering
about the library as a place.

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:03.780
And the transformative power
of stories, users withdrew

00:20:03.780 --> 00:20:05.970 position:56%
from libraries over the generations.

00:20:05.970 --> 00:20:09.440
So to explain my findings,
my challenge became how

00:20:09.440 --> 00:20:12.110
to expand beyond the
professional discourse,

00:20:12.110 --> 00:20:14.030
how to see outside the boundaries

00:20:14.030 --> 00:20:17.500
of librarianship's
limited sandbox of ideas.

00:20:17.500 --> 00:20:20.030
How to craft a framework
that accommodated

00:20:20.030 --> 00:20:24.220
and explained the voices of
library users I was uncovering

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:25.970
in my research.

00:20:25.970 --> 00:20:29.600
To illustrate the importance
of library in place,

00:20:29.600 --> 00:20:31.830
let me introduce you to Rickie.

00:20:31.830 --> 00:20:33.500
This is one of the trailers.

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:38.380
&gt;&gt; I live in San Francisco, and
I've been here for about a decade.

00:20:38.380 --> 00:20:42.640
And I'm current unemployed
but I do go to school.

00:20:42.640 --> 00:20:43.940
My apartment is about this big.

00:20:43.940 --> 00:20:48.670
And I don't have any
room for a desk.

00:20:48.670 --> 00:20:53.730
And so I come to the
library to do my homework.

00:20:53.730 --> 00:20:56.650 position:56%
But it's also just a great resource.

00:20:56.650 --> 00:21:02.880
I like to come to the gallery and
see what shows they have going on.

00:21:02.880 --> 00:21:04.980
I come to lectures, I come
to see films that they do.

00:21:04.980 --> 00:21:06.480
Mayoral debates, I've been here
for a couple of those as well.

00:21:06.480 --> 00:21:08.310
I mean, the reason that I'm here is
because I think it's just important

00:21:08.310 --> 00:21:10.110
for people to understand.

00:21:10.110 --> 00:21:15.550
[ Silence ]

00:21:15.550 --> 00:21:24.810
So when I first moved to San
Francisco, I told you I was broke.

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:30.100
And I was literally starving.

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:40.710
And I had a place to live,
but the library kept me warm.

00:21:40.710 --> 00:21:47.670
And it didn't -- I'll get it
together here in a second --

00:21:47.670 --> 00:21:50.950
There was a truck that
came outside once a week

00:21:50.950 --> 00:21:57.840
and we could go and get food there.

00:21:57.840 --> 00:22:03.340
And like I said, they had computers
so that I could work on my resume

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:05.180
and I could apply for jobs.

00:22:05.180 --> 00:22:08.800
And did I mention that
it was warm here?

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:14.910
So it's been there for
me when I needed it.

00:22:14.910 --> 00:22:17.010
It's a valuable resource.

00:22:17.010 --> 00:22:21.520
And oftentimes I think that people
see the library as some place

00:22:21.520 --> 00:22:24.900
for kids or some place
for homeless people.

00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:28.790
And there are just
normal people like me

00:22:28.790 --> 00:22:30.360
that might need it as a resource.

00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:31.730
So I'm grateful that it's here.

00:22:31.730 --> 00:22:33.030
&gt;&gt; Wayne Wiegand: And
from my narrative,

00:22:33.030 --> 00:22:35.690
I quote a few more anecdotes.

00:22:35.690 --> 00:22:43.280 position:56%
During the summer of 1939 at Atlanta
Public Library's African-American

00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:49.980
Branch, one of the few places in
the city where Blacks felt safe

00:22:49.980 --> 00:22:53.050
and welcomed, 10-year-old
Martin Luther King Jr. came

00:22:53.050 --> 00:22:56.440
to the library many
times during the week,

00:22:56.440 --> 00:23:00.810
Director Annie Waters
later recalled.

00:23:00.810 --> 00:23:05.300
"He would walk up to the desk
and look me straight in the eye."

00:23:05.300 --> 00:23:08.920
"Hello, Martin Luther," she
would respond, always calling him

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:10.470
by his first and middle names.

00:23:10.470 --> 00:23:12.120
"What's on your mind?"

00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:14.360
"Oh, nothing particularly."

00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:19.030
For Waters, that was a cue that
King had learned a big new word.

00:23:19.030 --> 00:23:23.820
And then they initiated
a conversation

00:23:23.820 --> 00:23:26.790
in which King used
the word repeatedly.

00:23:26.790 --> 00:23:28.620
Another game involved poetry.

00:23:28.620 --> 00:23:31.300
Again, King would stand
by the desk waiting.

00:23:31.300 --> 00:23:33.820
"What's on your mind,
Martin Luther?"

00:23:33.820 --> 00:23:35.120
Waters would ask.

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:36.460
"For I dipped into the future far

00:23:36.460 --> 00:23:39.610
as the human eye could
see," he responded.

00:23:39.610 --> 00:23:42.680
Waters immediately recognized
the poem and finished the verse,

00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:45.970
"Saw a vision of the world and
all the wonder that would be."

00:23:45.970 --> 00:23:54.160
When the Cincinnati Public Library
opened a piano room in 1955,

00:23:54.160 --> 00:24:01.360
among its first visitors was
12-year-old Jimmy Levine,

00:24:01.360 --> 00:24:06.820
as he wrote his name in pencil
on the room sign-up sheet.

00:24:06.820 --> 00:24:11.640
Eight visits later, he changed
his signature to J. Levine.

00:24:11.640 --> 00:24:13.510
And finally James Levine.

00:24:13.510 --> 00:24:19.290
When he gave a concert for 150
children in the children's room

00:24:19.290 --> 00:24:27.160
in 1957, he'd already performed
as a Cincinnati symphony soloist.

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:32.730
Today he's the New York
Mets' artistic director.

00:24:32.730 --> 00:24:42.250
In 1969, the Gary, Indiana Public
Library sponsored a local talent

00:24:42.250 --> 00:24:45.580
contest at which a group soon to be
known as the Jackson Five competed.

00:24:45.580 --> 00:24:48.990
Although they didn't win, little
Michael was an audience favorite.

00:24:48.990 --> 00:24:54.270
Okay, I'm going to bring it home
to the District of Columbia.

00:24:54.270 --> 00:24:58.750
In fiscal year 1914-1915,

00:24:58.750 --> 00:25:04.540 position:56%
the District of Columbia Public
Library reported auditorium meetings

00:25:04.540 --> 00:25:09.570
of the Housekeeper's Alliance
on Parcel Post, attendance 3307.

00:25:09.570 --> 00:25:14.570
Women's Single Tax League, six
meetings, average attendance 164.

00:25:14.570 --> 00:25:17.420
The Washington Readers
Club, 381 attending.

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:19.890
Intercollegiate Socialist Society,

00:25:19.890 --> 00:25:24.250
two meetings, average
attendance 188.

00:25:24.250 --> 00:25:29.790
German Readers Club, two
meetings, average attendance 312.

00:25:29.790 --> 00:25:33.610
The Wanderlusters, 413 attended
a lecture on Our Common Birds.

00:25:33.610 --> 00:25:41.960
And the Washington Theosophical
Federation, 348 attendees.

00:25:41.960 --> 00:25:46.350
Groups using its study rooms
included the American Racing Pigeon

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:52.160
Association, the Capitol
Poultry and Pigeon Association,

00:25:52.160 --> 00:25:58.030
the National Catholic Women's
Art Circle, the Painters

00:25:58.030 --> 00:26:01.810
and Decorators Union, a variety
of suffrage organizations,

00:26:01.810 --> 00:26:05.020
and three different
chapters of the Daughters

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:07.480
of the American Revolution.

00:26:07.480 --> 00:26:11.320
Ten years later, Chevy
Chase branch of the District

00:26:11.320 --> 00:26:12.860
of Columbia Public Library.

00:26:12.860 --> 00:26:15.070
The Woodbine Circle of the Chevy
Chase Methodist-Episcopal Church

00:26:15.070 --> 00:26:18.620
hosted a fashion review of
the latest women's wear,

00:26:18.620 --> 00:26:21.900
from sport costumes and
afternoon dresses to hosiery

00:26:21.900 --> 00:26:23.910
and lingerie, 225 attended.

00:26:23.910 --> 00:26:28.600
Readings, chorals, and orchestra
music supplement the review.

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:32.500
No report on whether men
were allowed to attend.

00:26:32.500 --> 00:26:37.380
In World War II at the District
of Columbia Public Library,

00:26:37.380 --> 00:26:39.820
the Petworth Branch became
a site for Government Girls.

00:26:39.820 --> 00:26:46.640 position:56%
These were women who came to D.C.
for wartime work, to gather in front

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:52.840
of burning logs in the fireplace
and listening to Victrola concerts.

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:55.780
Much of the edge of the loneliness

00:26:55.780 --> 00:26:57.860
of the first Washington
Sunday afternoon

00:26:57.860 --> 00:27:02.770
for the Government Girl has
been taken off by attendance

00:27:02.770 --> 00:27:06.040
at these concerts, and much
pleasure has been afforded her

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:10.490
on succeeding Sunday afternoons,
the Washington Post reported.

00:27:10.490 --> 00:27:14.570
Instead of an austere
resort of the literati,

00:27:14.570 --> 00:27:20.590
the District of Columbia Public
Library reported in 1842,

00:27:20.590 --> 00:27:26.700
listen carefully, "The libraries
are now becoming community centers

00:27:26.700 --> 00:27:28.050
through their use as a meeting
place for air raid workers,

00:27:28.050 --> 00:27:29.350
Red Cross workers, and
other civil defense workers.

00:27:29.350 --> 00:27:31.620 position:56%
In 2005, the Washington Post carried
an article by Eric Wee that focused

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:33.060
on the District of Columbia
branch library in one

00:27:33.060 --> 00:27:34.360
of Washington's poorest
neighborhoods.

00:27:34.360 --> 00:27:35.660
In it we reported that

00:27:35.660 --> 00:27:36.960
"Every Tuesday night a homeless
man named Conrad Cheek entered the

00:27:36.960 --> 00:27:38.260
library and set up
his chest board on one

00:27:38.260 --> 00:27:39.560
of the tables in the
children's room.

00:27:39.560 --> 00:27:40.860
We immediately noticed the
transformation taking place.

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:42.160
No more ignored pleas for this
homeless man, no averted glances.

00:27:42.160 --> 00:27:43.460
During the next hour, people
will look him in the eye.

00:27:43.460 --> 00:27:44.760
They'll listen to his words.

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:46.060
In this down-at-the-heels
library, he's the teacher.

00:27:46.060 --> 00:27:47.360
Among his students was
9-year-old Ali Osmond [assumed].

00:27:47.360 --> 00:27:48.660
As we watched this interaction,
Ali's mother explained

00:27:48.660 --> 00:27:49.960
that her son's confidence had
soared after playing with Conrad.

00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:51.260
That he was now bragging to
friends about being a chess player.

00:27:51.260 --> 00:27:52.560
We owe it all to Mr.
Conrad, his mother said.

00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:53.860
We love him.

00:27:53.860 --> 00:27:55.160
Inside the library, we reported,
they call him Mr. Conrad."

00:27:55.160 --> 00:27:56.460
Notice all these very
meaningful experiences occurred

00:27:56.460 --> 00:27:57.760
in a place we call library.

00:27:57.760 --> 00:27:59.060
But to categorize them as
information gathering fails

00:27:59.060 --> 00:28:00.360 position:56%
to capture their significance in the
lives of each of these individuals.

00:28:00.360 --> 00:28:01.660
My analysis of library
as place grows

00:28:01.660 --> 00:28:02.960
out of a scholarly literature
often labeled "public sphere,"

00:28:02.960 --> 00:28:04.260
a rich repository of ideas that
can deepen our understanding

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:05.560
of the multiple reasons why
people love their public libraries

00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:06.860
as community places.

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:08.160
Now let me turn to the
transformative potential

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:09.460
of commonplace stories public
libraries have circulated

00:28:09.460 --> 00:28:10.760
by the billions for generations.

00:28:10.760 --> 00:28:14.920
&gt;&gt; My birthday was yesterday,
and I am 95 years old.

00:28:14.920 --> 00:28:19.820
I started to use the library,
I would consider, well,

00:28:19.820 --> 00:28:28.810
at 13 years old, you know?

00:28:28.810 --> 00:28:32.910
I was born in [inaudible] Russia.

00:28:32.910 --> 00:28:37.420 position:56%
We left and we started from scratch.

00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:40.640
And my English was zero.

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:44.940
But the area library was
a couple of blocks away.

00:28:44.940 --> 00:28:48.930
And that's how it started.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.460
That library was everything to me.

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:56.310
We couldn't afford to buy books.

00:28:56.310 --> 00:29:01.870
Books were always expensive, and
there were so many other needs,

00:29:01.870 --> 00:29:06.410
it was library, library,
library all the time.

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:11.020
And it didn't cost anything.

00:29:11.020 --> 00:29:16.640
But the library fills a
certain place in my life

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:19.490
to satisfy certain needs.

00:29:19.490 --> 00:29:21.210
[Inaudible].

00:29:21.210 --> 00:29:25.620
And you just can't live
all the time with bad.

00:29:25.620 --> 00:29:27.610
You have to balance it.

00:29:27.610 --> 00:29:34.990
And my balance was mostly
to see something beautiful.

00:29:34.990 --> 00:29:40.710
And so I would go to the library
and spend a couple of hours.

00:29:42.560 --> 00:29:48.320
But when I come out on the street,
I'm a completely different person.

00:29:48.320 --> 00:29:53.010
It gave me such a relief,
as the French would say,

00:29:53.010 --> 00:29:55.510
[speaking French], you know?

00:29:55.510 --> 00:30:00.090
[ Silence ]

00:30:00.090 --> 00:30:02.510
&gt;&gt; Wayne Wiegand: And more
anecdotes from my narrative.

00:30:02.510 --> 00:30:07.990
In a 2008 interview, 88-year-old
Pete Seeger recalled an early life

00:30:07.990 --> 00:30:09.290
reading experience.

00:30:09.290 --> 00:30:13.380
"At age 7, a librarian recommended
me a book about a teenager

00:30:13.380 --> 00:30:15.900
who runs away from his
stepfather who's beating him.

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:19.880
And is adopted by a middle-aged
Indian whose tribe was massacred

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:23.670
and whose wife was sold into
slavery, and is living alone."

00:30:23.670 --> 00:30:26.270
That he remembered this
so vividly 80 years

00:30:26.270 --> 00:30:29.770
after reading it is testimony
to the power of stories.

00:30:29.770 --> 00:30:33.890
And in Seeger's case, a New York
Times editor noted upon his recent

00:30:33.890 --> 00:30:39.110 position:56%
death, "Fitting for someone who went
on to engage issues of conscience."

00:30:39.110 --> 00:30:43.270
In 1984, President Ronald
Reagan wrote the daughter-in-law

00:30:43.270 --> 00:30:48.200
of Harold Bell Wright, whose
bestselling 1920's religious novel,

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:50.850
"That Printer of Udell's"
Reagan read

00:30:50.850 --> 00:30:53.690 position:56%
as an adolescent in Dixon, Illinois.

00:30:53.690 --> 00:30:57.140
Wright was no favorite of
contemporary literary critics.

00:30:57.140 --> 00:31:01.990 position:56%
H.L. Mencken called him "a liberated
yokel from the cow and hog states."

00:31:01.990 --> 00:31:04.170
Another critic was equally harsh.

00:31:04.170 --> 00:31:06.880
"Harold Bell Wright
supplies more negative data

00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:08.930 position:56%
on the literary quality of the taste

00:31:08.930 --> 00:31:12.890
of the fiction-reading public
than any other author."

00:31:12.890 --> 00:31:15.270
No matter to young Reagan, however.

00:31:15.270 --> 00:31:18.550
Shortly after reading the
book he declared himself saved

00:31:18.550 --> 00:31:20.470
and was baptized.

00:31:20.470 --> 00:31:22.000
The novel's protagonist,

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:27.140
Reagan writes daughter-in-law 60
years later, served as a role model

00:31:27.140 --> 00:31:29.700
that shaped his life ever since.

00:31:29.700 --> 00:31:34.720 position:56%
It's highly likely the copy of "That
Printer of Udell's" Reagan read came

00:31:34.720 --> 00:31:37.820
from the Dixon Public Library,
which he visited twice a week

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:41.590
in the early 1920's, mostly
to check out Frank Merriwell

00:31:41.590 --> 00:31:46.680
and Sherlock Holmes stories, Tarzan
novels, and books by Horatio Alger,

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:48.400
Zane Grey, and Mark Twain.

00:31:48.400 --> 00:31:52.070
Many of which he read on
the library's front steps.

00:31:52.070 --> 00:31:55.440
"I'm a sucker for hero
worship," he later admitted.

00:31:55.440 --> 00:32:00.740 position:56%
For Oprah Winfrey,"Reading
commonplace stories was an open door

00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:03.440
for freedom in my life,
and allowed me to see

00:32:03.440 --> 00:32:06.330
that there was a world beyond
my grandmother's front porch

00:32:06.330 --> 00:32:07.630
in Mississippi.

00:32:07.630 --> 00:32:09.230
That everybody didn't
have an outhouse.

00:32:09.230 --> 00:32:11.820
That everybody wasn't
surrounded by poverty.

00:32:11.820 --> 00:32:16.190
That there was a hopeful world out
there, and it could belong to me."

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:20.690
To Winfrey, the stories became "her
comfort, her solace to commune with

00:32:20.690 --> 00:32:22.370
and learn something about myself.

00:32:22.370 --> 00:32:24.330
To learn something
about other people.

00:32:24.330 --> 00:32:27.050 position:56%
To learn something about the world."

00:32:27.050 --> 00:32:31.210
In a small Milwaukee apartment
as a 9-year-old in 1963,

00:32:31.210 --> 00:32:35.040
she read a public library copy
of "A Tree Grows in Brooklyn,"

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:36.660
her first all-night book.

00:32:36.660 --> 00:32:40.100
The story of Francine Nolan, whose
life was full of humiliation.

00:32:40.100 --> 00:32:44.400 position:56%
And whose only friends were in books
lining the public library shelves.

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:49.660
"I felt like my life
was hers," she said.

00:32:49.660 --> 00:32:52.510
After her father died in 1963,

00:32:52.510 --> 00:32:55.790
9-year-old Sonia Sotomayor
buried herself in reading

00:32:55.790 --> 00:32:58.730
at her Bronx library and
the apartment she shared

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:00.740
with her mother and brother.

00:33:00.740 --> 00:33:05.410
"Nancy Drew had a powerful hold on
my imagination," she remembered.

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:09.280 position:56%
"Every night when I finished reading
and got into bed and closed my eyes,

00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:12.520
I would continue the story
with me in Nancy's shoes.

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:14.250
Until I fell asleep."

00:33:14.250 --> 00:33:18.360
Her mind, she noted, worked in
ways very similar to Nancy's.

00:33:18.360 --> 00:33:20.190 position:56%
"I was a keen observer and listener.

00:33:20.190 --> 00:33:23.850
I picked up on clues, I
figured things out logically.

00:33:23.850 --> 00:33:25.710
And I enjoyed puzzles.

00:33:25.710 --> 00:33:29.910
