00:34:12.640 --> 00:34:16.250
"constitute recipes
for the imagination."

00:34:16.250 --> 00:34:18.520
Media scholar Henry Jenkins adds,

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:21.110
"Stories are basic to
all human cultures.

00:34:21.110 --> 00:34:25.200
A primary means by which we
structure, share, and make sense

00:34:25.200 --> 00:34:27.300
of our common experiences."

00:34:27.300 --> 00:34:28.600
Meet Danny.

00:34:28.600 --> 00:34:31.760
&gt;&gt; One of the things I'd say
the library offered me was

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:35.520
that it was a place where I could
actually [inaudible] American

00:34:35.520 --> 00:34:36.820
pop culture.

00:34:36.820 --> 00:34:38.500
I grew up in an immigrant
household, so I was --

00:34:38.500 --> 00:34:42.000
the library for me was always the
place where I could get free media.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:46.090
When I was a teenager,
I was really big

00:34:46.090 --> 00:34:49.060
into punk rock culture
and the music scene.

00:34:49.060 --> 00:34:53.210
And I couldn't afford records, so
I was always going to the library.

00:34:53.210 --> 00:34:56.920
Whereas my friends were able
to either buy their records

00:34:56.920 --> 00:34:58.220
with their parents' money.

00:34:58.220 --> 00:34:59.620
Or, worse yet, steal it.

00:34:59.620 --> 00:35:02.320
I'd always go to the
library and check them out.

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:09.190
When I was a teenager -- I think I
might have been like 15 years old,

00:35:09.190 --> 00:35:13.810
I had heard about a film
called "A Beautiful Thing."

00:35:13.810 --> 00:35:15.760
Which is based on a play.

00:35:15.760 --> 00:35:17.120
And it's a gay film.

00:35:17.120 --> 00:35:21.490
I remember going to the library
and looking up in the catalog

00:35:21.490 --> 00:35:23.590
and making sure nobody saw me.

00:35:23.590 --> 00:35:27.390
And I went to the stacks
and found it,

00:35:27.390 --> 00:35:31.030
I kind of hid it underneath a
stack of books, like sandwiched

00:35:31.030 --> 00:35:32.760
between a stack of books.

00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:35.480
And I checked it out.

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:40.570
I took this video home, had
to hide it from my parents.

00:35:40.570 --> 00:35:43.870
And I remember watching this film
and it was so powerful to me.

00:35:43.870 --> 00:35:54.560
It was a love story between
two young British teenagers.

00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:59.870
And for me it dropped a
certain anchor down where

00:35:59.870 --> 00:36:05.020
on an emotional level I didn't feel
like I was floundering, somehow.

00:36:05.020 --> 00:36:06.850
So that felt really good.

00:36:06.850 --> 00:36:13.520 position:56%
And I remember playing that cassette
tape, that VHS tape over and over

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:18.340
and over again late at night
when everyone else was sleeping,

00:36:18.340 --> 00:36:22.090
I'd sneak out to the living
room and I'd play this video

00:36:22.090 --> 00:36:28.970
that I had borrowed from the
library, like at least once a night

00:36:28.970 --> 00:36:32.000
for three weeks in a row.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:37.060
Sometimes repeating certain
scenes over and over again.

00:36:37.060 --> 00:36:42.090
Just because for me,
they really spoke to me.

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:43.970
And then I would renew it.

00:36:43.970 --> 00:36:45.270
[Laughter].

00:36:45.270 --> 00:36:46.570
&gt;&gt; Wayne Wiegand: That public
libraries have always played a

00:36:46.570 --> 00:36:48.380
primary role in making
stories accessible

00:36:48.380 --> 00:36:50.800
to millions of users is obvious.

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:54.980
Ever since the Boston Public
Library opened in 1854, fiction,

00:36:54.980 --> 00:37:00.470
a particular form of story,
consistently averaged 66 to 75%

00:37:00.470 --> 00:37:02.980
