00:42:35.550 --> 00:42:38.930
For generations now, library and
government officials have argued

00:42:38.930 --> 00:42:42.550
that the public library's most
important role is to provide access

00:42:42.550 --> 00:42:46.260
to useful information that
develops intelligent consumers,

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:49.820
creative entrepreneurs,
and informed citizens.

00:42:49.820 --> 00:42:53.880 position:56%
The kind of information Thomas
Edison pursued in his public library

00:42:53.880 --> 00:42:57.740
that many argued people can now
retrieve on their computers.

00:42:57.740 --> 00:43:00.730
At home. Public library
users, however,

00:43:00.730 --> 00:43:03.180
show a different set of priorities.

00:43:03.180 --> 00:43:07.140
For them, the tens of thousands
of spaces public libraries provide

00:43:07.140 --> 00:43:09.230
for many purposes, and the billions

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:12.450
of commonplace stories
they circulate in a variety

00:43:12.450 --> 00:43:15.920
of textual forms, are at
least as important as --

00:43:15.920 --> 00:43:20.260
perhaps even more important
than -- access to information.

00:43:20.260 --> 00:43:23.120
And for a variety of reasons.

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:26.400
In her book, "The Village Effect:

00:43:26.400 --> 00:43:31.920 position:56%
How Face-to-Face Contact Can Make
Us Healthier, Happier, and Smarter,"

00:43:31.920 --> 00:43:35.230
Susan Pinker harnesses research
in the fast-developing field

00:43:35.230 --> 00:43:38.140
of social neuroscience
to demonstrate

00:43:38.140 --> 00:43:40.780
that substantial benefits
accrue to those

00:43:40.780 --> 00:43:44.390
who experience high levels
of face-to-face contact.

00:43:44.390 --> 00:43:48.700
Including improved vocabularies,
an increased ability to empathize,

00:43:48.700 --> 00:43:50.140
a deeper sense of belonging.

00:43:50.140 --> 00:43:54.770
And perhaps most important,
a longer life span.

00:43:54.770 --> 00:43:57.940
Neuroscientific research
that focuses specifically

00:43:57.940 --> 00:44:01.300
on the social nature of
commonplace reading comes

00:44:01.300 --> 00:44:02.930
to similar conclusions.

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:06.230
"Fiction," notes research
psychologist Keith Oatley,

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:08.880
